response:
```graph
digraph G {
    rankdir=LR;
    node [shape=box];

    Thermistor [label="NTC Thermistor"];
    Buffer [label="Buffer Amplifier"];
    Linearization [label="Linearization Network"];
    GainStage [label="Gain Stage"];
    LevelShifter [label="Level Shifter"];
    OutputBuffer [label="Output Buffer"];
    AntiAliasingFilter [label="Anti-Aliasing Filter"];
    ADC [label="Analog-to-Digital Converter"];

    Thermistor -> Buffer;
    Buffer -> Linearization;
    Linearization -> GainStage;
    GainStage -> LevelShifter;
    LevelShifter -> OutputBuffer;
    OutputBuffer -> AntiAliasingFilter;
    AntiAliasingFilter -> ADC;
}
```

```Explanations
NTC Thermistor: This block represents the temperature-sensing element, a Vishay NTCLE100E3 NTC thermistor. Its resistance decreases as the temperature increases. The thermistor needs to be part of a circuit that converts the change in resistance to a change in voltage, which can be further processed.

Buffer Amplifier: This block provides impedance isolation between the thermistor and subsequent stages. It prevents the thermistor's varying resistance from affecting the downstream circuitry, which could otherwise cause non-linearities or loading effects.

Linearization Network: Since the relationship between resistance and temperature for a thermistor is non-linear, a linearization network is used to convert the non-linear resistance changes of the thermistor into a more linear voltage change. This could involve a resistor network or an active circuit designed to achieve a linear response over the desired temperature range of 10 to 90 degrees Celsius.

Gain Stage: After linearization, the signal is typically very small and needs to be amplified to utilize the full scale of the output range. This block amplifies the signal to ensure the output voltage will cover the 0 to 20 Volts range for easy measurement with a multimeter.

Level Shifter: This stage is responsible for shifting the voltage level of the signal so that the lowest temperature corresponds to 0 Volts and the highest temperature corresponds to 20 Volts output. This is important for matching the output to the multimeter's expected input range.

Output Buffer: The purpose of this buffer is to provide a low output impedance to drive the multimeter or any other subsequent measurement device without being affected by its input impedance. This ensures the voltage remains stable and accurate regardless of the load presented by the multimeter.

Anti-Aliasing Filter: Although the project is specified to be in the analog domain, if there is an ADC present, this block is crucial for removing high-frequency components from the signal to prevent aliasing when the signal is digitized.

Analog-to-Digital Converter (ADC): This block converts the analog signal into a digital value that can be processed or displayed by digital systems. It is included here for completeness, in case the analog voltage needs to be interfaced with digital equipment. However, if the project is purely analog without any digital display, this block would be omitted.
```

